\f0 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 The context\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec4 As 2023 begins, public services are under immense pressure. The combined impact of 13 years of\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Conservative underfunding, neglect, and mismanagement, a global pandemic, soaring energy costs, and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 spiralling in\uc0\u64258 ation is limiting services\'92 ability to give security and support to communities around the country.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 The NHS in England went into the pandemic with an acute sta\uc0\u64259 ng crisis and a waiting list that had soared\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 from 2.4 million in 2010 to 4.4 million in 2020. Now, services are faced with a backlog of care and are not yet\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 back to pre-pandemic activity levels. Preventative services are lagging behind; almost one million fewer\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 women a year are being screened for breast and cervical cancer compared to a decade ago. Despite\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 huge shortfalls and inequalities in women\'92s healthcare, the Government has failed to deliver on its own\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 women\'92s health strategy. Urgent and emergency care is in crisis. Ambulance crews routinely queue for\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 hours outside hospitals because A&E departments are full, and the average response time to someone who\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 has had a suspected stroke or heart attack is 48 minutes.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Meanwhile, mental health services are facing extraordinary demand as people reel from the impact of\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 isolation and hardship, with children and young people particularly a\uc0\u64256 ected. 44 per cent of children and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 young people who are referred for urgent treatment for an eating disorder wait three months or more.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Community care services haven\'92t got enough sta\uc0\u64256  to prevent people from going into hospital, and neither\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 do they have capacity to support all those who need continuing care after leaving. England has lost more\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 than 4,000 GPs and a \uc0\u64257 fth of all GP practices over the last decade. Now, millions of people wait over a\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 month to see their GP and public satisfaction with GP services has fallen to 38 per cent - the lowest level\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 since records began and 39 percentage points below Labour\'92s last year in government.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Long-promised social care reforms have been postponed again, leaving thousands unable to access care.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Almost 35,000 people a year are estimated to die whilst waiting for social care, whilst almost 6,000 a year\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 run out of savings paying for their own care. This leaves unpaid carers to \uc0\u64257 ll gaps, with families forced to take\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 time out of work and lose income in order to care for their loved ones, often with little support or respite.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 In education, schools are being squeezed by soaring energy costs and will see no net growth in spending\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 per pupil from 2010 \'96 2024. Schools cannot \uc0\u64257 ll vacancies, school buildings are crumbling and attainment has\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 su\uc0\u64256 ered as a result of pandemic disruption. Children who are disabled and those with special educational\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 needs (SEND) are particularly disadvantaged by the Conservatives\'92 lack of ambition, with 1,500 children\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 with SEND who should be in education still waiting for a place at school. Further education is su\uc0\u64256 ering after\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 a sustained period of Conservative neglect, while anticipating a predicted 160,000 extra students by 2024,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 and our world-class universities are becoming \uc0\u64257 nancially unviable, with standards driven down for sta\u64256  and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 students as a result of the Government\'92s broken funding system and failed higher education policies.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Children\'92s social care is in a desperate state. Local authorities are often life lines for vulnerable children\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 and families, but do not have the resources they need to reach those who could bene\uc0\u64257 t from support and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 intervention. This leaves too many vulnerable children at risk and facing disadvantage simply because of\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 the circumstances in which they were born.\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Meanwhile, the dedicated sta\uc0\u64256  in our public services are working overtime to \u64257 ll workforce gaps and meet\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 record demand, without the fair pay and recognition they deserve. Many public service employees are\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 considering or taking industrial action as a result \'96 for example, in winter 2022/23 the Royal College of\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 Nursing in England took country-wide strike action for the \uc0\u64257 rst time in its history.\cf0 \cb1 \
